James de Villiers, News24 Court. (Duncan Alfreds, News24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town - A former Oudtshoorn municipal manager found guilty of fraud amounting to more than R2m will be sentenced in the Oudtshoorn Regional Court on Friday.&nbsp;Martin No&euml;l Pietersen, 60, was found guilty in December of contravening the Local Government Finance Act when he awarded an open-ended contract to IBR consultants in 2010 without following proper procedures, Hawks spokesperson Captain Lloyd Ramovha said in a statement.&nbsp;"[He] used his position or privileges of accounting officer for personal gain to improperly benefit another person, namely Ian Kenned from IBR consultants," Ramovha said.&nbsp;Kenned is believed to have received 23 payments totalling R2 069 050 without verification of the value of services the municipality received.&nbsp;"[Pietersen] abused his authority arbitrarily incurring overspends... to accommodate payments to IBR and attempted to rectify these overspends through adjustment budgets mechanisms," Ramovha said.&nbsp;At the time of Pietersen's conviction Hawks head Berning Ntlemeza said he was elated by the ruling.&nbsp;"This is only the beginning, we are buoyed by this ruling and we shall continue to discharge our mandate with assurance and vigour," he said.&nbsp;24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.